You want to be able to share variables without using static.  There&#39;s an 
easy way to do this using JUnit, but you lose out on dynamic suite 
generation unfortunately.

import junit.framework.*;
/**
  * Accepts arguments at runtime
  **/
public class RuntimeArgumentsTest extends TestCase {

     private final String[] args;

     public RuntimeArgumentsTest(String[] args, String name) {
         super(name);
         this.args = args;
     }

     public void testStuff() {
         assertNotNull(args);
         assertEquals(args[0], &quot;hi&quot;);
     }

     public static Test suite() {
         TestSuite suite = new TestSuite();
         String[] args = new String[] { &quot;bye&quot; };
         suite.addTest(new RuntimeArguments(args, &quot;testStuff&quot;));  // this 
will fail
         args = new String[] { &quot;hi&quot; };
         suite.addTest(new RuntimeArguments(args, &quot;testStuff&quot;));  // this 
will pass
         return suite;
     }
}

Hope that helps.  There&#39;s got to be a way we can keep this behavior 
without losing the ability to dynamically generate the suite, right?

Regarding the license, JUnit is actually using the IBM Common Public 
License.  If it were using the GPL, however, you only have to publish 
your changes if you distribute the binary.  If you&#39;re only using JUnit 
for in house testing--and you don&#39;t distribute it--you don&#39;t *have* to 
distribute your changes (though it is a nice act, if they&#39;re not totally 
specific to your project).

